segments.text: At the time, you see, I left right at the tactile end of all of that, but as I recall, I had simply made the assumption that when that was all over, the Board of Regents and the Board of Directors at the time were very supportive of it.
I know that Pete Peterson had been active in the association, and he later was the name to the Board of Regents.
and there was a kind of a carryover of leadership on the board that had been involved either through the association's work or some way where it did with the university.
Sterling Evans by then is on the board.
Do you remember any role that he played?
I don't remember any role that Sterling played during the
century study, I assume he was a member of the...
I think he was.
I'm sure he was one of them.
But my memory of Sterling Evans was the fact that he was a student loan fund trustee of the associations for many years, and I worked with him for 17 years.
And long about that time or before,
We had three trustees.
One was Sterling Evans, one was Jimmy Aston from Dallas, and one was a fella, Estelle, that was president of the big bank in Fort Worth.
And we'd meet usually in Fort Worth and Dallas for dinner.
And during those discussions, we would talk about student life.

And that's when I recall more than any other time Sterling expressing his opinions to these other two men that something was going to have to be done at A&M and that was to let the girls come and to let them make that call.
And he was one of them.
Before John Lindsay, he was one of the other ones that back in the early days had the vision to realize that we needed to do something.
Do you have any idea who it was put their arm around Earl Rudder's shoulder and kind of said, come on, Earl, let's go with it?
My guess would be it was Harold Dunn.
My guess it would be Harold Dunn, because Harold was the chairman of the century staff.
And he was very involved with it.
And he knew psychology.
And he knew that Earl was scared to death and was not willing to really back him.
And I don't know, but I'm guessing it would have been well done.
Now, I may sound to be a little critical of Earl, but I want to be truthful about the way it all came out.
And I'll say this without fear of blind addiction.
I don't think a single person in the world could have pulled this off.
Except?
Except our old brother.
Now I say he drugged his feet, which I think he did.
I don't think he won, which I don't think he did.
I don't think he won the name check, but he probably did.
And I don't think that we could have had another version at the time.
that could have rolled with the punches, stayed in there, worked with the legislature, and got this thing done.
Now Earl had a lot of help, but he was a driving force in bringing people like you and a lot of people you know to this campus.
Well, let me put into this.
a little connection.
As the Secretary of the Aspirations Report, it was my job to write the draft of the report, particularly on RISL, Resident Instruction Student Life.
The other part on research and extension was easy, do more better.
So it was my job then to write up the part arguing for, justifying, non-compulsory core
racial integration, women, higher admission requirements, and so forth.
I turned it in to Wayne Hall, the Vice President of Academic Affairs.
He called me back three or four days later, gave me the copy that Mr. Rutter had read and annotated.
He told me to revise it, bring it in line with Mr. Rutter's comments, a number of which were negative.
Who prepared that?
The original, or I did.
You prepared it and sent it to Rutter and he made some notes on it.
And where'd you get this?
This is a bunch of crap.
No way.
I go back to Vice President Hall a few days later and said, I can't in good faith make those changes because the committee.
That's not the report.
That's right.
That.
Our opinions are subjective.
We may be in error, but we do believe that A&M has got to make these changes.
And I always am proud to say, to recall that he said, I'll stake my job on your right to speak what the committee really believes.
And so I turned it back, didn't hear any more.
I then forgot to turn back in the copy with Mr. Rutter's comments.
About two months later, one Sunday morning,
Got a call from Dorsey McCrory.
We were on our way to Sunday school in the garage.
Where was that copy?
In my office in Nagel Hall.
I'll get it to you in a few days.
He said, I'll meet you at Nagel Hall in 10 minutes.
And I'm guessing that somebody had told him, get that report.
Earl.
Yeah, that's my guess.
Earl told him to get it.
So I gave it back to him.
I don't know whether it still exists or not.
I never had any call from anybody to try to pressure me or anything else.
And I don't know that any member of the committee did.
But we all admitted that we were surprised when we voted unanimously for all these changes that each of us thought he might be a minority of one or two.
And we were pleasantly surprised that it went on.
Are you aware of whether or not the board
of directors, then called board directors, did they have any long debates over this or do you know?
I do not know.
I do not know.
I don't even have a copy of that report.
I got it when I left the association.
I just didn't think about taking a copy of that report.
I remember when it was done and I just thought it was a beautiful piece of work.
Didn't Bob Hunt prepare one first and it was thrown out the window?
I think so.
I think that Bob Hunt prepared one, but not acceptable.
And I remember talking to Darcy and talking to Wayne Hall to some extent.
And they said, well, we're going to redo it.
And I think I knew at that time that they'd moved it over to you to prepare.
But I don't remember.
I think that everybody was so relieved and so pleased with the report and the decisions that came out that we all just assumed that it was going to be approved by everybody.
Now, how much debate did the board have?
I doubt that they had very much.
We never heard of any rumors or hints that there was any division when the board did
I don't recall any division on the part of the board.
I think the board was very informed and knew all about this century study that was being conducted.
And they knew what was happening.
And I think that they were prepared for it all when it came out.
I remember the name change was one of the biggest things that happened in the whole thing.
By that time we realized that we were going to have integration.
I'm sure we had some blacks already by that time.
I can line it up.
Did you hear, I never heard any opposition to integration, did you?
No, no.
I never heard a rumble over that.
I didn't hear a thing.
The only thing I heard was the late women, the optional, and the name check.
even though Bill Moore, in a moment of not much attendance, got a Senate resolution passed making the Corps optional.
And nobody hardly knew about what was happening.
And this caused quite an uproar.
This was before the century started.
Now, Moore was for the changes, wasn't he?
Yes, very much so.
Moore was for optional coal.
Moore was for co-education.
He was for the name change.
He was for integration.
I don't think he was on the century study, because he was a state senator.
But he was for the .
Now, Brownrigg Dewey was our representative.
And as far as I know, he was quietly low key for.
Low key for.
Brownrigg never talked much about it.
But Bill Moore was.
Boy, he was strong.
And you know Bill and Earl were like this.
And they tried not to fire me.
But Bill Moore had talked to Earl, and I didn't know it, about making the former student's office move off the campus.
And I didn't know it.
Because?
Because they claimed that I talked very impugned.
into running against Biltmore.
I didn't know all this was going on.
We had an executive board meeting, and we had the meeting, right at the end of the meeting, President, somebody said, by the way, we've got this problem we need to talk about.
And I said, what's the problem?
And they said, Biltmore is old enough to be unhappy with you.
And Pew was running against change, wasn't he?
Wasn't he opposed to the changes?
Well, probably.
Marion Pugh?
Probably.
Okay.
But this situation had nothing to do with the Century Senate.
Oh, okay.
He was running for the Senate.
Bill Moore had announced he was running for the State Senate against Bill Moore.
Somebody had told Bill Moore that me personally had talked Marion Pugh into it.
Therefore, he was mad at me and he was mad at the association.
We had this meeting.
I said, I did not have one thing in the world to do with it.
The first time I knew that Pew was running against Bill Moore was when I saw Pew's picture of the eagle.
And I just told him honestly.
I said, I'm telling you, I didn't know a thing about it.
Wayne Durham from Abilene was on our board.
He was a good friend of Bill Moore last night.
And I forgot who was president of the association there, but they said, well you go to Austin and talk to Bill Moore.
Tell Bill Moore that the association and Herbie had nothing to do with Pew electing to run against you, which I didn't.
And he went and talked to Bill Moore.
Bill Moore just forgot about it.
And later on,
Bill Moore and I got to be close friends, still are.
And I think I'm partly responsible for getting Earl and Bill Moore together, and they did.
Now, I heard third-hand reports that by sheer coincidence, during some of those months of debate,

two automobiles would drive with their lights off into the parking lot behind the campus theater at about 10 o'clock at night and these two total strangers would roll down their driver's side window and would chat with this total stranger in the other vehicle and that a close observer if he had walked by might have realized that this was the state senator and the A&M president who just accidentally happened to be there chatting with each other but they
They then could also say, whomever those strangers were, that they had never really talked about this with the other one.
Deep throat?
Yeah.
During your time with the association, did the association ever engage in any activity in Austin for anything?
Well, yes.
Did you all lobby for better appropriations?
We lobbied mainly, we lobbied for better appropriations as far as we could under our charter.
We wouldn't do anything to question our tax status.
And you can't try to enforce legislation and maintain the type of tax status we had.
So we were very careful about that.
But we did lobby.

Whenever our permanent university fund was questioned, and we had more or less committees among our 180 A&M clubs, those that were located in Texas, to be prepared upon the receipt of the telephone to go back.
And I mean first team back.
We had some of the top stud horses in every town.
Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, San Antonio, Parks Christian, Abilene, El Paso, Texarkana, Tyler.
We had the state, every senatorial district, 31 in Texas.
And we had committees, standing committees lined up.
Ready to go.
Ready to go.
And every once in a while we had to use them.
And we put them into effect.
And here go the phone calls and the letters to the people from those districts.
And we did mostly work on the university fund to protect it.
There were always people trying to invade the university fund.
Another thing too, we were active in getting legislation passed that provided for funding for these other schools outside the University of Texas system.
Now let's see, the governors that you worked with would have been... Well, John Connolly.
Connolly.
Then before him, Shivers.
Shivers and Smith.
And Buford Jester?
To some extent, early.
That was before Alan Shivers.
That was in right after the war, 46, 47, 48.
Buford Jester and then Shivers.
And then who after Shivers?
Was it Conley or was it Smith?
I believe it's Conley.
Conley, yeah.
And during Conley's administration is when Maggie Lee had such an influence in
traveling all over the state about, well, when Earl came here, Earl sat down in the car, I remember you talked about deep throat.
Earl and I would travel around in the car a lot, and he showed me one day, he said, you know what the average salary of a professor at A&M is?
This would have been in 57 or 58 or 59.
58, probably.
He came here in 57.
The average salary of a professor.
And I said, that's got to be increased.
We came that way.
And that's when we got Maggie to provide his airplane.
We got Tom Harrington early.
I had a pair of guns held.
We got Logan Wilson from the University of Texas.
We put in some money to provide to, we hired this guy, he was a bearded man from Austin, a lot as you may know.
You may remember him.
And he was more or less a staff director.
He'd been a lobbyist and he helped us.
to improve, well first, we did a selling job to the people of Texas, the big people of Texas, on the importance of our education in Texas.
The fact that we were losing the top of our herd, our best faculty people, to out of state institutions.
They were going, leaving here by the droves, not going to stay in Texas, going up there where they appreciated us.
I think you were on some of these trips, weren't you?
We'd get the top people in Houston, like Beaumont, or Houston, or Dallas, or Fort Worth, Abilene.
We'd get the top people up there, mostly Haitians, Dallas, to pay for the dinner.
That was the first thing we did.
We got a sponsor.
Once we got the sponsor, then we invited the top people, like Dallas.
We had the mayors of all these, and we had state senators, and we had members of the legislature from those areas come, and Tom Harrington and Logan Wilson were the main speakers.
Every once in a while Earl would do some talking, and Ransom, Ransom was his name?
Harry Ransom.
Harry Ransom from Austin would do the talking.
But we tried to keep Logan Wilson and Tom, because Tom could make a good speech.
Oh yeah.
And that's about the same time that Connery came up with this sales tax.
And I don't know whether he dedicated the sales tax to education,

He used education as a reason for selling the people of the state of Texas on the sales tax and so that whole effort was very important and I think more than anything else, even though we did include the other state schools, it really focused to the people of Texas the importance
of the University of Texas system and the A&M system to the state.
And we didn't exclude North Texas State, we didn't exclude the East Texas, Southwest, and all the rest of them.
We included them, but we were the forces.
Let's go back to the Deans.
We had an interruption and we were getting ready to talk about Frank Hubert.
Frank Hubert.
Frank was my number one contact, I think, except for maybe Earl and Darcy and Wayne.
I didn't deal too much with Wayne.
But Frank had been brought in here by Earl.
Do you know what the connection was there?
Did they know each other in Austin?
Because Hubert was J.W.
Edgar's right-hand man at the Department of Education for a while in Austin.
In Austin.
And I was wondering if they knew each other then.
I'm going back and trying to recollect.
Earl needed help, and he needed some.
for good health when he first came back here.
And I remember some of those first people that he drew were Frank Hubert.
And I'm assuming, see Frank had been superintendent of schools at Orange.
That's right.
Was my high school principal.
All right, your high school principal.
And he went with Mr. J.W.
Edgar in Austin.

and that was a key role in state at the time and I'm thinking that when Earl was at Austin, when he was in politics more or less with a land commuter job and getting elected job and supporting Lyndon Johnson that he and Frank were involved and
He brought John Calhoun into here from wherever John was, wherever John was.
Penn State.
Penn State.
He brought John into Penn State.
And he brought, let me think a minute, this man that later went to Oklahoma State, Bob Com.
Com.
He brought Bob Com in the same time he brought John Calhoun in.
Who else along that time?
He brought...
Frank Hubert.
Now where did you find Dorsey McCrory?
I got the Dorsey.
I was Dorsey's room hardy.
Oh.
And Darcy under the Thomason Act went into the service.
Earl talked to me he said I wanted an assistant and I want a retired, I want a reserve officer and I want somebody that's got an A&M degree.
And I wanted to be my sister.
You gotta be somebody to be recognized by the enemy.
But my first recommendation was Dave Hitch.
You remember Dave Hitch?
I went to Earl and I said, Dave Hitch, he's your man.
And Earl called Dave Hitch.
Dave Hitch didn't want, he didn't want to leave Davis Field.
So Earl called me and said, we struck out on
For your first suggestion, I said, all right, I got another one.
I had talked to Darcy at a class reunion or two.
He wanted to get out of the military.
He was a full colonel in the Army.
And I had known that he had gone to Yale and gotten a master's degree in Yale, but he was a reserve officer.
And he wanted a position with the university.
I guess it later proved off that I more or less made a mistake.
Anyway, I went to Earl and I said, your man is a little colonel named McCrory.
And he said, well, can you get him down and talk to me?
And I said, yeah.
I called him and gave him Earl's telephone number.
And I said, if he wants to talk to me, you got to make arrangements to get him in.
He talked to Earl and the Army didn't want to let him go because he just finished this Naval War College or Army War College.
Anyway, Earl said, if you want to come and if you will come, if you will accept the money, I'll pay you.
I'll get you separated from the Army.
And I got him a house he moved into when we first came.
I did all that stuff.
Yeah, I got Darcy here.
And Ed Cooper, did he go to work for Mr.
Rudder while you were still?
Yeah, I was involved in that too.
Earl was working in the, not Earl, but Ed Cooper was working in the extension service.
I think so.
He finished A&M in 53 and
I had people call me wanting to employ somebody to run that maritime thing in Galveston.
And I called them and I said, Ed Cooper's your man.
I said, Ed Cooper?
Well, Ed went down and interviewed these people and for some reason they couldn't quite get together, but they were gonna pay him.
salary two or three times what he was making a year.
Anyway, I had gotten acquainted with Ed and become fond of Ed.
And then when Ed, by reason of Ed left the university, went to work with Broach in the
oil business for a while.
He had been, I'm not sure he'd been in Earl's office before then or not.
I guess I'm kind of doubting.
Anyway, Buck was running the association and Ed Cooper had left the college trying to make a fortune in the oil and gas business and that didn't work out.

And they found a position for him over there, and then I guess when Dorsey, sometime in there, during Earl's time, not during Jack Williams' time, during Earl's administration, I guess maybe Dorsey brought him in there, and Dorsey went over to the development office.
Dorsey went to the development office in 61, about.
This young man, John Lindsay.
John Lindsay.
When did he become active in the former student?
He was active in the former students when I came back here in 1947.
So he already...
He was already active in the former students program.
Very active.
He was on the councils and he was on the committees and he was involved in Houston.
Anytime you needed anything in Houston, you'd count on John Lindsay to step forward with it.
He was, we would have the A&M meetings around and he would be present, not in the big open meetings, but in the smaller full session type meetings when he was most effective.
That's when he would shake his fingers and just let the girls come to the A&M.
Can't keep them out anymore.
We had past presidents meetings around every year.

mostly a social event, but all the old-class presidents would come back and we'd have a meeting somewhere at a resort or somewhere, and I recall at those meetings, John would, and Earl would be president, a lot of them, and John would say, fellas, we can't operate like we operated in 1972.
This is 1955, or this is 19, we've got an 18 girls' committee.
And John was talking it, but nobody else would even mention girls.
But John was saying, we've got to move this forward.
I remember a meeting we had down at Key Allegro in Rockport.
Mr. Krueger's son, Carl Krueger, developed that whole thing.
And he had us down there one time, he said he asked me, John, made a speech to the people and we started picking up on them.
Harold Dunn started realizing, Jimmy Astin started realizing, Bobby Krueger, Mr. Tyree Bell, and some of those real leaders started saying, well, we've got to do something.
We've got to do something.
That was in the days when
most of the old die-in-the-wool Aggies like Charlie Babcock.
I wouldn't think of a girl ever coming to him.
I know Mr. Babcock's opposition.
Who were the other most vocal, active opponents?
Well, T.L.
Smith, Jr. used to be Mr. Charlie Babcock for the most vocal.
